China Life, China Unicom, Zijin Mining: Hong Kong Stock Preview

-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a
-- 
2011-08-24T23:54:09Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-24/china-life-china-unicom-zijin-mining-hong-kong-stock-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in  Hong Kong  trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the close yesterday.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  fell 2.1 percent to 19,466.79. The Hang
Seng China Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, fell 3.1 percent to 10,255.63.  Mining companies: A measure of primary metals traded in
 London  climbed for a second day, rising 0.1 percent yesterday.  Jiangxi Copper Co. (358 HK), China’s No. 1 producer of the
metal, lost 2.4 percent to HK$19.92. Aluminum Corp. of China Ltd.
(2600 HK), the listed unit of nation’s biggest maker of the
lightweight metal, gained 0.2 percent to HK$5.18.  Oil stocks: Crude oil for October delivery fell 0.3 percent
on the  New York Mercantile Exchange  yesterday.  PetroChina Co. (857 HK), the nation’s largest oil company,
sank 2.5 percent to HK$9.34.  Cnooc Ltd. (883)  (883 HK) lost 2.1 percent to HK$14.22. China’s
biggest offshore oil explorer posted record half-year profit
after crude prices rose and it increased output to meet demand
in the fastest-growing major economy.  Gold producers: Gold futures for December delivery plunged
5.6 percent on the Comex in  New York  yesterday.  Zijin Mining Group Co. (2899 HK), China’s largest gold
producer by market value, fell 1.6 percent to HK$3.69.  Bank of China Ltd. (3988)  (3988 HK): The nation’s third-largest
lender by assets said first-half profit jumped 28 percent to a
record as loan and fee income climbed. Net income increased to
66.5 billion yuan ($10.4 billion) from 52 billion yuan a year
earlier, the Beijing-based company said in a Hong Kong stock
exchange statement. The stock lost 2.3 percent to HK$3.01.        Brilliance China Automotive Holdings Ltd. (1114)  (1114 HK): The
Chinese partner of Bayerische Motoren Werke AG said first-half
profit rose 85 percent as rising incomes spurred luxury-car
demand in the world’s largest auto market. The stock slumped 6.9
percent to HK$8.47.       China Life Insurance Co. (2628 HK): The nation’s biggest
insurer said it may consider a bond sale in Hong Kong to bolster
its capital after stock and debt market declines eroded its
profit and solvency margin. Its shares plunged 12 percent to
HK$20.30.       China Shipping Container Lines Co. (2866 HK): The nation’s
second-largest container carrier posted a net loss of 630
million yuan in the first half compared with net income of 1.17
billion yuan the same period a year ago. The stock rose 0.5
percent to HK$1.88.  China  Unicom (Hong Kong) Ltd. (762 HK): The nation’s
second-largest mobile phone company said net income in the
second quarter rose 78 percent to 2.49 billion yuan, according
to figures derived from first-half earnings reported by the
Beijing-based company. Profit exceeded the 969 million yuan
average of four analysts’ estimates compiled by Bloomberg. China
Unicom added 0.4 percent to HK$13.70.       CSR Corp. (1766 HK): China’s biggest trainmaker said its
units have agreed to contracts or won bids on contracts ranging
from 400 million yuan to 2.55 billion yuan. The contracts were
with China Railway Investment Corp., the Ministry of Railways,
the Ministry of Railway Transport of  Turkmenistan , Iranian Rail
Transportation Co. and Wuhan Metro Group Co. CSR fell 3.9
percent to HK$4.44.       Li Ning Co. (2331 HK): China’s largest maker and retailer
of sportswear posted a 49 percent decline in first-half net
income as higher costs and increased competition cut margins. It
also said its gross and profit margins may narrow. The stock
fell 3 percent to HK$9.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Shani Raja in Sydney at 
